arn about a family of orchid farmers who are replanting a mountainside to attract native pollinators. Meet a bumblebee expert helping Wisconsin cranberry growers, a bark beetle specialist in a new-growth forest in Georgia, an entomologist collecting for the Essig Museum in California, and more. Against a backdrop of climate change, ecological injustice, and impending mass extinction, this book rekindles wonder and hope.Featuring works by artists deeply invested in preserving the smallest beings among us, Where the Grass Still Sings is a paean to the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBiodiversity conservation. 0aInsects in art. 0aInsectsxConservation. 0aInsectsxEcology. 7aNATURE / Essays.2bisacsh  aInsects.  aagro-ecology.  aart.  abeetles.  abiodiversity.  abumblebees.  abutterflies.  aconservation.  aenvironmental activism.  aenvironmental justice.  aenvironmental literature.  afrogs.  ainsect apocalypse.  amoths.  aorchids.  aorganic farming.  aprairie restoration.  aresilience.  awasps.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079776340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098326?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098326/original  a978-3-11-079776-3  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles